# Commit Style

Conventions for commit messages and commit structure. Tooling-agnostic — applies whether
you're using `git`, `jj`, or anything else. This is the default guide bundled with the
`commit` skill; if the repo you're working in ships its own commit-style guide or PR template,
that takes precedence.

A commit is a message to two audiences:

1. **The reviewer today**, who needs to understand intent before reading the diff.
2. **You in three years at 2 am**, diagnosing a regression and trying to understand whether the
   change in this commit is supposed to interact with the change just deployed yesterday.

For both audiences clarity, rationale, and brevity are the most important properties.

---

## High-level structure

Every commit **must** have:

- a subject line in Conventional Commits format
{{ if $ticketRequired -}}
- a ticket line in the body that either links to a tracking issue or explains why this commit
  doesn't touch production code (this guide writes it as `Jira:`; use your repo's convention)
{{ end -}}
- a body describing the **effect** of the change.

---

## Subject line

```
<type>(<scope>): <imperative summary>
```

- **Imperative mood, sentence case, no trailing period.** "Add", "Fix", "Drop" — not "Added",
  "Adds", "Adding". Capitalize the first word; the subject is a title, not a sentence. The
  commit completes "If applied, this commit will…".
- **Conventional Commits prefix**: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `perf`, `test`, `docs`, `chore`,
  `build`.
- **Scope** is a project or component (e.g. `api`, `loader`, `auth` — use the names your repo
  already uses). Optional if the repo doesn't scope subjects.
- **Concrete summary.** "Fix host eval" is useless. "Fix host eval dropping rows when cve_id is
  null" is a subject line.
- **≤ 70 characters.** GitHub truncates around 72; leave headroom.

Bad:

```
Updated the feeds manager and added some tests.
fixed bug
feat(TICKET-2456): changes to the way we load feeds and refactored loader.
```

Good:

```
feat(vfm): Support paginated feed loads
fix(observer-host): Drop rows where cve_id is null after dedup
docs: Mention that foo's bar table is read by service quux
chore(spark-jobs): Thread context.Context through database logs
```

---

## Body

GitHub-flavored Markdown. Use `##` headings for sections. Section length is proportional to the
change — skip a section if it adds no value, and don't invent ceremony for a one-line typo fix.

{{ if $ticketRequired -}}
### Ticket line first

Every body **must** open with a ticket line. Acceptable forms (this guide uses `Jira:`):

```
Jira: https://your-tracker.example.com/browse/TICKET-2463
Jira: TODO
Jira: This commit only touches documentation
```

`Jira: TODO` is acceptable while drafting but must be replaced with a real link before the PR
opens. If you're an AI agent writing a commit and the user hasn't supplied a ticket, ask for
one and offer `Jira: TODO` only as a placeholder — never invent a ticket key.
{{- else -}}
_This machine does not use a ticket line; commit bodies open directly with the effect. (If the
current repo's own guide or history clearly uses ticket references, defer to the repo.)_
{{- end }}

### Body

Every description **must** start with an explanation of the effect of the change — what
behavior, capability, or guarantee changes for users, callers, or the system — not the
implementation. A reviewer should be able to read the description and know what is now
different about the running system, without needing the diff to make sense of it.

Exception: for chore/refactor PRs where the implementation is the point (e.g., docs updates,
dependency bumps, file moves), describing the implementation is appropriate, since that is the
effect.

Effect examples:

- Good: Vulnerability ingestion now retries transient upstream 5xx errors instead of dropping
  the batch.
- Bad: Wrapped fetchBatch in a retry.Do with exponential backoff in ingest.go

- Good: Added a prometheus metric that will allow us to alert on database rows dropped.
- Bad: Call db.call.err.inc() on errors

If the change has no system effect (docs, comments, formatting, build-script tweaks), there is
nothing to put first — the body is just *Why*. Don't compensate for the missing effect by
enumerating what each file gained; that's restating the diff, which `git show` already does.

#### Possible sections

Default to *Why* only. If the **why** is obvious from the commit body then just provide a
**what**. Add another section only if the commit can't be understood without it — the list
below is a menu of options, not a checklist to fill in. If you find yourself reaching for three
or more sections on a change with no system effect, you are probably writing a tour of the
diff.

- **Why** — what was the world like before this commit, and why was that wrong? Always present,
  even if implicit in good prose.
- **Notes for reviewer**: where to start reading; what to focus on; what's intentionally out of
  scope.
- **Implementation**:
  - designs that were attempted and rejected ("tried to use a hashmap instead of a list
    but...")
  - tradeoffs that were considered and are valid but were not chosen, along with why.
- **Verification** / **Tests** — CI runs the test suite and failures will be obvious and
  prevent merge. Mention (and link to!) additional verification that was performed that is
  infeasible to incorporate into CI.
  - Concrete: the QA env you deployed to with a link to logs, the smoke report you compared,
    the dashboard you watched.
    - **Useless verification:** "Tested locally. All tests pass."
    - **Useful verification:** "Ran `VulnObserverHostITCase` against a 30-day prod advisory
      snapshot; row counts match the pre-change baseline within 0.01%. The 412 spurious rows
      from the last smoke run are gone." The reviewer cannot see your query or that you ran the
      job in QA for 3 days — provide links or copy-pasteable text they can use to perform the
      verification themselves or convince themselves it's useful.
- **Risks** — known dangers and why they're unavoidable. Include for changes where the exact
  effect isn't provable in CI. Present **only** if there **is** some risk and mitigations must
  be considered.
- **Follow-ups** — things deliberately deferred, with a ticket link.

---

## Things that belong in the commit, not in the source

| Information | Commit message | Source comment |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Why this change is happening today | **yes** | no |
{{ if $ticketRequired -}}
| Ticket reference | **yes** | no |
{{ end -}}
| What was tried and rejected during this change | **yes** | no |
| Why the code is structured the way it is (still true today) | no | **yes** |
| Invariants, gotchas, performance characteristics | no | **yes** |
| Narrative history ("we used to do X, now we do Y") | **yes**, if X is gone | Usually no, **yes**, if X is the reason we still do Y |

The commit message captures the choice as it was made; the source comment captures the choice
as it must be maintained.

---

## Things that don't belong in a commit message

- **Restating the diff.** "Added a new function `foo` to `bar.go`" — `git show` already says
  that. Tell us why.
- **AI co-author trailers.** No `Co-Authored-By: Claude …`, `Generated-with: …`, or similar.
- **Re-explaining the project.** The reader knows what the component is — they're reading its
  history.
- **Re-documenting documentation.** You've updated the docs, just point the reader to them.

---

## Commits within a PR

Many repos squash-and-merge PRs. Where they do, the PR title and body become the merged commit
and are the canonical artifact — they must follow the rules above. Individual commits on the
branch do not survive the merge.

That means only the **lead commit** of a PR (and the PR title and body itself) needs a fully
style-conformant message. Follow-up commits — review responses, fixups, incidental cleanups —
can use a lighter prefix that names the *kind* of cleanup:

- `review-response: <what>` — addressing review feedback
- `fixup: <what>` — small fix to an earlier commit on this branch
- `cleanup: <what>` — incidental polish

Follow-ups {{ if $ticketRequired }}don't need a ticket line (the lead carries it) and {{ end }}don't need a body unless the
change is non-trivial. Conventional Commits format (`fix(scope): …`) is still fine for a
follow-up that's a self-contained logical change.

---

## Changes that span multiple PRs

For schema migrations, large rewrites, and stacked PRs:

- Each PR's title and body must stand on its own — don't write a description that only makes
  sense if you've read the previous PR. Stacked PRs squash-merge into their base branch (not
  always `main`), so each PR's message must be self-contained even when `Builds on #N` provides
  the cross-link.
- The first PR's body sketches the overall arc and links to the design doc or epic ticket.
- Subsequent PRs reference prior PRs in the body (`Builds on #32301`), not in the subject.
- Don't use commit messages to coordinate ordering — that's what the PR description and the
  ticket are for.

---

## Examples

**Change descriptions should be as brief as possible.** Pick the size by reviewer risk, not
LOC:

- **Brief** is the default. Use it whenever the diff is self-explanatory and the reader only
  needs the *Why*.
- **Medium** is for changes where the reviewer needs context the diff doesn't carry — a
  non-obvious tradeoff, evidence the fix works, a subtle invariant.
- **Detailed** is for changes a reviewer cannot safely approve from the diff alone: multi-file
  refactors, behavior changes whose effect must be verified out of band, schema-touching work,
  anything cross-cutting.

A large diff does not entitle a commit to a long description. A docs rewrite or a mechanical
rename is *Brief* even if it touches a hundred files.

### Brief

```
docs: Mention that foo's bar table is read by service quux

{{ if $ticketRequired -}}
Jira: This commit only touches documentation

{{ end -}}
This took some investigation, so capture it in the doc comment on BarDao
where the next reader of that file will find it.
```

### Too long (anti-pattern)

Same scope as the Brief example above — a docs-only update — written badly:

```
docs: Mention that foo's bar table is read by service quux

{{ if $ticketRequired -}}
Jira: This commit only touches documentation

{{ end -}}
## Why

The relationship between foo and quux was undocumented anywhere in the
repo, and on-call engineers were repeatedly tracing it from logs at 2am.

## Effect

- BarDao now has a doc comment naming quux as a reader.
- The package-level Javadoc has been updated to cross-reference BarDao.
- A pointer from quux's README points back to BarDao.

## Notes for reviewer

The doc comment on BarDao is the easiest path into the change.
```

The *Effect* section is a tour of the diff — `git show` already lists those three changes.
*Notes for reviewer* is ceremony for a three-line doc comment. The Brief version above says
everything that matters in two sentences.

### Medium

```
fix(observer-host): Drop rows where cve_id is null after dedup

{{ if $ticketRequired -}}
Jira: https://your-tracker.example.com/browse/TICKET-32418

{{ end -}}
## Why

The advisory join in `VulnObserverHostJob` was producing rows with null
`cve_id` when a host package matched an advisory whose CVE list had been
retracted upstream. These rows survived the dedup step (which keys on
`host_id + cve_id`) and inflated smoke-report row counts by ~0.3%.

## Verification

Re-ran the smoke report against the prod 30-day snapshot; the 412
spurious rows from the last run are gone and overall row count is
within 0.01% of the pre-bug baseline.

Link to shared worksheet: https://example.com/worksheets/c0ffee
```

### Detailed

````
refactor(advisory-loader): Extract OS package metadata writer into its own job

{{ if $ticketRequired -}}
Jira: https://your-tracker.example.com/browse/TICKET-30119

{{ end -}}
## Why

`VulnAdvisoryLoaderJob` has accreted three responsibilities: loading
raw advisories, normalizing them, and writing the OS package metadata
table. The third has a different cadence (hourly vs daily) and a
different failure mode (idempotent overwrite vs append) than the other
two, and keeping them in one job has forced us to gate the metadata
write behind a config flag that's on in prod and off everywhere else.

This split also unblocks the schema-evolution work in TICKET-30122,
which needs to evolve the metadata table on a different cadence than
the advisory tables.

## Implementation

Move the metadata write into `VulnAdvisoryOsPkgMetadataUpdaterJob`.
This looks big, but there is no behavior change. The new job is
wired into the existing schedule in a follow-up commit; until then
the old code path is retained behind the same config flag, so this
commit is safe to land independently.

## Notes for reviewer

The new doc comment on `VulnAdvisoryOsPkgMetadataUpdaterJob` is the
easiest path into the change.

## Verification

- Diffed both jobs' output against the previous single-job output on
  a frozen prod snapshot; row counts and column hashes match exactly:

  ```sql
  -- this change
  SELECT COUNT(*) FROM ospkgmetadata WHERE created_time == '20260101T000000';
  -- previous version of the code
  SELECT COUNT(*) FROM ospkgmetadata WHERE created_time == '20251201T000000';
  ```

## Risks

None in this commit (no behavior change). The behavior change lands
in the follow-up.

## Follow-ups

- TICKET-30120: wire the new job into the scheduler.
- TICKET-30122: schema evolution for the metadata table.
````
